{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772048137,"nonce":"zU/OH/rzhkT7pUp8oCpptRAW5vk=","message":"[GitHub comment by i-m-mll on 2024-02-20T17:41:44Z]\n\nFor now, I've (6ff288d) moved the `CartesianState` operations to `PointMass`.\n\nNow `AbstractLTISystem.vector_field` looks like \n\n```python\n    def vector_field(\n        self, \n        t: float, \n        state: Array,\n        input: Float[Array, \"input\"]\n    ) -\u003e Array:\n        \"\"\"Returns time derivatives of the system's states.\"\"\" \n        return self.A @ state + self.B @ input\n```\n\n`PointMass` still inherits from `AbstractLTISystem`, and `PointMass.vector_field` looks like:\n\n```python\n    def vector_field(\n        self, \n        t: float, \n        state: CartesianState,\n        input: Float[Array, \"input\"]\n    ) -\u003e CartesianState:\n        \"\"\"Returns time derivatives of the system's states.\"\"\"\n        force = input + state.force\n        state_ = jnp.concatenate([state.pos, state.vel])       \n        d_y = super().vector_field(t, state_, force)\n\n        return CartesianState(pos=d_y[:2], vel=d_y[2:])\n```\n\nThis generalizes `AbstractLTISystem`, but maybe something should still be done to avoid concatenation.","files":null}]}